d Recreation: The Cultural Forum -- tIV TV Industry: Industrial Practices and Structures -- t25 The Ernie Kovacs Show: Historicizing Comedy -- t26 Gilmore Girls: A Year in the Life: TV Revivals -- t27 I Love Lucy: The Writer- Producer -- t28 Modern Family: Product Placement -- t29 The Real Housewives of Beverly Hills: Franchising Femininity -- t30 Roseanne: Programming Flow -- t31 Tales from the Crypt: Content Regulation -- t32 The Toy Box: Transmedia and Transgenerational Marketing -- tV TV Practices: Medium, Technology, and Everyday Life -- t33 Battlestar Galactica: Fans and Ancillary Content -- t34 Everyday Italian: Cultivating Taste -- t35 Gossip Girl: Transmedia Technologies -- t36 High Maintenance and The Misadventures of Awkward Black Girl: Indie TV -- t37 Monty Python’s Flying Circus: Layered Comedy -- t38 NFL Broadcasts: Interpretive Communities -- t39 Pardon the Interruption: Sports Debate -- t40 The Walking Dead: Adapting Comics -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new edition that brings the ways we watch and think about television up to the presentWe all have opinions about the television shows we watch, but television criticism is about much more than simply evaluating the merits of a particular show and deeming it “good” or “bad.” Rather, criticism uses the close examination of a television program to explore that program’s cultural significance, creative strategies, and its place in a broader social context.How to Watch Television, Second Edition brings together forty original essays—more than half of which are new to this edition—from today’s leading scholars on television culture, who write about the programs they care (and think) the most about. Each essay focuses on a single television show, demonstrating one way to read the program and, through it, our media culture. From fashioning blackness in Empire to representation in Orange is the New Black and from the role of the reboot in Gilmore Girls to the function of changing political atmospheres in Roseanne, these essays model how to practice media criticism in accessible language, providing critical insights through analysis—suggesting a way of looking at TV that students and interested viewers might emulate. The contributors discuss a wide range of television programs past and present, covering many formats and genres, spanning fiction and non-fiction, broadcast, streaming, and cable. Addressing shows from TV’s earliest days to contemporary online transformations of the medium, How to Watch Television, Second Edition is designed to engender classroom discussion among television critics of all backgrounds.To access additional essays from the first edition, visit the "links" tab at nyupress.org/9781479898817/how-to-watch-television-second-edition/.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aTelevision programsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision programsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision programszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAdaptation.  aAdvertising.  aAesthetics.  aAncillary.  aArchives.  aCable.  aCinematography.  aCitizenship.  aClass.  aComedy.  aComics.  aCooking.  aCrime.  aCriticism.  aCultural forum.  aCulture.  aDebate.  aDesign.  aDevelopment.  aDisabilities.  aDistribution.  aDrama.  aEditing.  aEducational.  aEntertainment.  aEthnography.  aEurope.  aFans.  aFashion.  aFeminism.  aFlow.  aFootball.  aFox.  aFranchises.  aGender.  aHistoriography.  aIdentity.  aIndependent.  aIndustry.  aIntersectionality.  aLicensing.  aMarketing.  aMasculinity.  aMeaning.  aMelodrama.  aMuslims.  aNarrativ